Business Scenario

Suppose you are a data analyst working for an airline company. You need to analyze flight data to understand delays and where the largest impacts occurred. You have access to flight data, airline information, and airport data.

Conditional Statements: if_else

An âif elseâ statement is used to execute different blocks of code based on whether a condition is TRUE or FALSE. The basic syntax is:

if (condition) {
  # Code to execute if condition is TRUE
} else {
  # Code to execute if condition is FALSE
}

Conditional Statements: case_when

The case_when() function in R, part of the dplyr package, is a powerful tool for creating new variables based on multiple conditions. It is similar to a series of if_else() statements but more concise and readable. The basic syntax is:

df %>%
  mutate(new_var = case_when(
    condition1 ~ value1,
    condition2 ~ value2,
    TRUE ~ default_value
  ))

Exercise 5: Create a new column using case_when

Create a new column that categorizes flights based on their departure delay:

  • On Time: Departure delay is 0 or less.

  • Short Delay: Departure delay is between 1 and 15 minutes.

  • Medium Delay: Departure delay is between 15 and 60 minutes.

  • Long Delay: Departure delay is more than 60 minutes.

In this example:

  • dep_delay <= 0 ~ âOn Timeâ assigns âOn Timeâ to flights with no delay or early departure.
  • dep_delay > 0 & dep_delay <= 15 ~ âShort Delayâ assigns âShort Delayâ to flights delayed by up to 15 minutes.
  • dep_delay > 15 & dep_delay <= 60 ~ âMedium Delayâ assigns âMedium Delayâ to flights delayed by up to 60 minutes.
  • dep_delay > 60 ~ âLong Delayâ assigns âLong Delayâ to flights delayed by more than 60 minutes.
  • TRUE ~ âUnknownâ acts as a catch-all for any other cases, ensuring no missing values.

Joins

Joins are used to combine data from two data frames based on a common column. The dplyr package provides several types of joins, each serving a different purpose.

  • Inner Join: An inner join returns only the rows that have matching values in both data frames.

  • Left Join: A left join returns all rows from the left data frame and the matched rows from the right data frame. If there is no match, the result is NA on the right side.

  • Right Join: A right join returns all rows from the right data frame and the matched rows from the left data frame. If there is no match, the result is NA on the left side.

  • Full Join: A full join returns all rows when there is a match in either left or right data frame. Rows without a match in one of the data frames will have NA in the respective columns.

Functions

A function in R is a block of code that performs a specific task. Functions help avoid repeating code and can make your code more organized and reusable. You can think of a function like a âmini-programâ that you can call whenever you need to do a certain task.

A function typically has:

  • A name: What you call the function (e.g., mean(), filter()).

  • Arguments: The inputs you pass into the function (e.g., a dataset, a value).

  • Body: The block of code that gets executed when the function is called.

  • Return value: What the function gives back after it finishes.
